<DOC><DOCNO> AP890522-0054 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 0953EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-CommencementBriefs SUB a0501 05-22 0145</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Commencement Briefs, SUB, a0501,0146</SECOND><HEAD>Civil Rights Leaders, Statesmen Address Graduates</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st item to fix typo in Morehouse.</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Rev. Allan Boesak criticized the UnitedStates for withholding sanctions against South Africa'swhite-minority government.   The South African civil rights activist urged 285 graduates ofMorehouse College on Sunday to make a difference ``not just bymaking money but by making history, not simply by standing to becounted but by standing where it counts.''   He criticized U.S. officials for allowing South Africa more timeto end apartheid.   ``More time for what?'' he asked. ``More time for detentionswithout trials? More time for the killing of our children in thestreet like dogs?''   ``The South African government should not be given more timebecause it is a government that has no right to exist,'' he said.</TEXT></DOC>